properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A short period of rain is expected. Total rainfall: 10 to 20 mm. Locations: western Newfoundland. Time span: early this evening until midnight tonight. Remarks: Rainfall amounts will be much lower than experienced earlier this week; however, after the recent flooding, some areas may still be sensitive to any rainfall that occurs. Interests in these locations should monitor local runoff for any potential vulnerabilities. The rain will taper to flurries or showers overnight. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snow and strong winds are expected. Total snowfall: 5 to 10 cm possible. Maximum wind gusts: 80 to 100 km/h in the Rigolet area and 100 to 120 km/h from Cartwright to Black Tickle. Time span: Saturday evening until early Sunday morning. Remarks: After a brief period of snow and rain tonight, conditions will improve for most of Saturday. However, snow is expected to develop again on Saturday evening with strong northwesterly winds. Snow and blowing snow may significantly reduce visibility for several hours on Saturday night. Wind warnings are anticipated; blowing snow advisories may also be required. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.

properties.Title: Winter Storm Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snow, blowing snow and strong northwesterly winds are expected. Total snowfall: 20 to 30 cm. Maximum wind gusts: 120 km/h. Locations: Hopedale to Makkovik. Time span: overnight tonight until early Sunday. Remarks: Snow will begin this evening before strong northwesterly winds develop overnight to cause poor visibility in blowing snow. Stormy conditions will persist through Saturday and then improve overnight Saturday night into early Sunday. ### Visibility will be suddenly reduced to near zero at times in heavy snow and blowing snow. properties.Summary:
Description: Brief, intense snowfall is expected to develop. Under the snow squall, visibilities will be significantly reduced due to the heavy snow. Snow squall watches are issued when conditions are favourable for the formation of bands of snow that could produce intense accumulating snow or near zero visibilities. Description: Strong winds are expected or occurring. Maximum gusts: locally 100 km/h in the Wreckhouse area. Time span: approximately 3 P.M. today until 9 P.M. tonight. properties.Title: Snow Squall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snow squalls are occurring. Under the snow squall bands, visibilities will be significantly reduced due to the heavy snow, and snow will quickly accumulate. Snowfall accumulations will be highly variable. The Yellowknife airport has reported 11 cm since snow began last night and some areas may see an additional 5 to 10 cm before snow squalls end this afternoon. ### Snow squall warnings are issued when bands of snow form that produce intense accumulating snow or near zero visibilities. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NTstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NTStorm.
